The paper discusses the application of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to signals defined on graphs, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several computer science subfields. Based on the content of the abstract, the most likely category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), as the paper proposes a new CNN architecture that operates on graph-structured data. The second most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), as CNNs are widely used in image processing and the proposed architecture is designed to handle irregularly structured signals. The third likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), as graphs are often used to model social networks and other types of information networks. The fourth likely category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), as the paper deals with neural networks and their design. Finally, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is a possible category, as the paper discusses the use of graph filters to process signals on graphs, which involves algorithmic and data structure considerations.
